    <section type="subsubsection">
      <title>Case <number>4</number>: Co-ordinate or dative covalent bonds</title>
      <definition><term>Dative covalent bond</term><meaning>This type of bond is a description of covalent bonding that occurs between two atoms in which both electrons shared in the bond come from the same atom.</meaning></definition>
       <para>A dative covalent bond is also known as a coordinate covalent bond. Earlier we said that atoms with a pair of electrons will normally not share that pair to form a bond. But now we will see how an electron pair can be used by atoms to form a covalent bond.</para>
        <para>One example of a molecule that contains a dative covalent bond is the ammonium ion (<chem_compound>NH_{4}^{+}</chem_compound>) shown in the figure below. The hydrogen ion <chem_compound>H^{+}</chem_compound> does not contain any electrons, and therefore the electrons that are in the bond that forms between this ion and the nitrogen atom, come only from the nitrogen.</para>
        <pspicture>
          <code>
            (-.5,-1)(9.5,1)
\rput(0.1,0){\Large \textbf{H}}
\rput(1,0){\Large \textbf{N}}
\uput{9pt}[d](1,0){\scalebox{0.8}{$\times$ $\bullet$}}
\rput{90}(1,0){\uput{9pt}[d](0,0){\scalebox{0.8}{$\times$ $\bullet$}}}
\rput{180}(1,0){\uput{9pt}[d](0,0){\scalebox{0.8}{$\bullet$ $\bullet$}}}
\rput{270}(1,0){\uput{9pt}[d](0,0){\scalebox{0.8}{$\times$ $\bullet$}}}
\rput(1,-0.8){\Large \textbf{H}}
\rput(1.9,0){\Large \textbf{H}}
\rput(2.8,0){\Large \textbf{+}}
\rput(4,0){\Large \textbf{[H]$^{+}$}}
\psline[arrows=-&gt;](5,0)(6,0)
\rput(6.8,0){
\rput(0.1,0){\Large \textbf{H}}
\rput(1,0){\Large \textbf{N}}
\uput{9pt}[d](1,0){\scalebox{0.8}{$\times$ $\bullet$}}
\rput{90}(1,0){\uput{9pt}[d](0,0){\scalebox{0.8}{$\times$ $\bullet$}}}
\rput{180}(1,0){\uput{9pt}[d](0,0){\scalebox{0.8}{$\bullet$ $\bullet$}}}
\rput{270}(1,0){\uput{9pt}[d](0,0){\scalebox{0.8}{$\times$ $\bullet$}}}
\rput(1,-0.8){\Large \textbf{H}}
\rput(1.9,0){\Large \textbf{H}}
\rput(1,0.8){\Large \textbf{H}}
\psline(2.1,0.8)(2.2,0.8)(2.2,-0.8)(2.1,-0.8)
\psline(-0.1,0.8)(-0.2,0.8)(-0.2,-0.8)(-0.1,-0.8)
\rput(2.5,0.8){\large \textbf{+}}
}
          </code>
        </pspicture>
                    <para>Notice that the hydrogen ion is charged and that this charge is shown on the ammonium ion using square brackets and a plus sign outside the square brackets.</para>
                    <para>We can also show this as:</para>
                    <pspicture>
          <code>
            (-.5,-1)(3,1)
\rput(0.1,0){\Large \textbf{H}}
\rput(1,0){\Large \textbf{N}}
\psline(0.35,0)(0.75,0)
\psline(1.25,0)(1.65,0)
\psline(1,-0.25)(1,-0.55)
\rput{180}(1,0){\uput{9pt}[d](0,0){\scalebox{0.8}{$\bullet$ $\bullet$}}}
\rput(1,-0.8){\Large \textbf{H}}
\rput(1.9,0){\Large \textbf{H}}
\rput(1,0.8){\Large \textbf{H}}
\psline(2.1,0.8)(2.2,0.8)(2.2,-0.8)(2.1,-0.8)
\psline(-0.1,0.8)(-0.2,0.8)(-0.2,-0.8)(-0.1,-0.8)
\rput(2.5,0.8){\large \textbf{+}}
          </code>
