    <shortcode>ESBMD</shortcode>
<para>So far we have looked at covalent molecules. But how do we know that they are covalent? The answer comes from electronegativity. Each element (except for the noble gases) has an electronegativity value.</para>
            <para><emphasis effect="bold">Electronegativity</emphasis> is a measure of how strongly an atom pulls a shared electron pair towards it. The table below shows the electronegativities of the some of the elements.</para>
			<para>For a full list of electronegativities see the periodic table at the front of the book. On this periodic table the electronegativity values are given in the top right corner. Do not confuse these values with the other numbers shown for the elements. Electronegativities will always be between <number>0</number> and <number>4</number> for any element. If you use a number greater than <number>4</number> then you are not using the electronegativity.</para>
